European debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley — — "That was just the Greek crisis," "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think, but that is no longer the case, because it is clearly a crisis in the euro zone.
Dealing with it is both easier and more difficult than usually expected.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
The banking sector in Ireland is problematic.
The private debt market in Portugal is problematic.
Spain has problems in all three areas mentioned above.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
The usual way to offset the side effects of austerity is to combine domestic spending cuts with depreciation of the domestic currency.
Depreciation can enhance the competitiveness of exports, which is to say, using foreign demand to compensate for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all members of the Eurozone, and they do not have an independent currency that can depreciate, so they can only substitute internal depreciation for external depreciation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs in order to increase the competitiveness of exports and achieve the effect of expanding foreign demand.
In fact, these crisis countries have made considerable efforts to tighten their belts.
However, there is one economic variable that has not changed along with the adjustment of other variables, that is, the debt of the public and private sectors.
The book value of the government's accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt —— except for some debts owed to junior creditors —— has also remained largely unchanged.
It is this simple fact that places the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relatively.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending must be cut and taxes increased to meet the debts of the government and its protectors (such as banks).
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, thus creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a depression.
Therefore, for the internal devaluation strategy to be effective, it is necessary to find a way to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and should be written off when banks are insolvent.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are reluctant to take this path.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is concerned about losing credibility in the financial markets.
If creditors are mainly from abroad, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not entirely unfounded, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose one of the two.
They unanimously ruled out the option of external devaluation.
However, internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both unreasonable and illogical.
The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debt instruments, whose face value is discounted at a certain ratio from the current debt face value.
Bondholders can choose either to stick with their bonds, redeeming them at face value but with a later maturity date and lower interest rate; or accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and higher interest rate.
This isn't cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to make it successful, there are three prerequisites.
First, it is necessary to guarantee the safety of the new bonds to bondholders.
Someone needs to come forward to guarantee these bonds.
During the Latin American debt restructuring under the Brady Plan in the 1980s, the United States Treasury played the role of the "guaranteeing elder brother."
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, debt restructuring in one country will raise expectations in other countries, leading to a ripple effect.
Finally, banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must consolidate their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, rather than the bureaucratic farce conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals insufficient capital, a comprehensive conversion of debt to equity must be carried out for the relevant banks.
If that is not enough, the government must inject capital into the relevant banks directly.
This too requires coordinated action by all countries.
Once banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have significant risk exposure to the debts of peripheral Eurozone nations, and the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should shoulder the responsibility of providing guarantees without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, especially German leaders, need to make the consequences sound more severe — otherwise, they will be in big trouble.
Because that's just the way it is.
